## Solution (Optional but recommended)
Context()->texStrings;

BEGIN_SOLUTION
$BBOLD Part (a) $EBOLD
Assuming we have \(N = 60\) observations, we have that the
next forecasted value would be
\[
\hat{x}_{60}(1) = $alpha \times $dat +  $beta \times z_{60} 
\]
where \(z_{60}\) is the observed residual ($dat - $dat_est). Hence the forecast is $data[0].
$BR
$BR
$BBOLD Part (b) $EBOLD
Recall that the MA representation of an ARIMA model via
\[X_t =\sum_{i=0}^{\infty }\psi _{i}Z_{t-i}
\]
enables prediction intervals. Assuming approximate Normality for the forecast errors an approximate \( \left( 1-\alpha \right) 100\)% prediction interval is given by 
\[
\hat{x}_{N}(l) \pm z_{\alpha /2}\hat{\sigma}\sqrt{\sum_{i=0}^{l-1} \hat{\psi}_{i}^{2}},
\]
where \(l\) is the lead time, \(z_{\alpha /2}\) is the \(\frac{\alpha }{2}\) percentage point of the \(N\left( 0,1\right)\) distribution and \(\hat{\sigma}\) is an estimate of the standard deviation of \(Z_t\). The weight {\( \psi _{i} \)} can be found by direct division or by equating coefficients in powers of \(B\) in 
\[\psi \left( B\right) \phi \left( B\right) =\theta \left( B\right) .\]
In this case the ARMA(1,1) process
\[
X_t =$alpha X_{t-1} +$beta Z_{t-1} +Z_t
\]
takes
\[
\phi \left( B\right) =1-$alpha B
\]
and
\[
\theta \left( B\right) =1+$beta B,
\]
defining a stationary and invertible process. Now
\[
\begin{eqnarray*}
\psi \left( B\right)  &=&\theta \left( B\right) \phi \left( B\right) ^{-1} \\ 
&=&\left( 1+$beta B\right) \left( 1-$alpha B\right) ^{-1} \\
&=&\left( 1+$beta B\right) \left( 1+$alpha B+$alpha^{2}B^{2}+$alpha^{3}B^{3}+\cdots \right)  \\
&=&1+\left( $alpha+$beta\right) B+\left( $alpha^{2}+$alpha\times $beta\right) B^{2} \\
&&+\left( $alpha^{3}+$alpha^{2}\times $beta\right) B^{3}+\cdots +\left( $alpha^{j}+$alpha^{j-1}\times $beta\right) B^{j}+\cdots .
\end{eqnarray*}
\]
Alternatively the ARMAtoMA command in R can be used; for instance ARMAtoMA($alpha, $beta, 3) gives the first three values, \(\psi _{1}, \psi _{2}\) and \(\psi _{3}\). The approximate 95% prediction interval for (a) is
\[
\hat{x}_{60}(1) \pm 1.96\times $sigma\sqrt{1},
\]
the lower bound being \( \hat{x}_{60}(1) - 1.96 \times $sigma = \) $data[1].
$BR
$BR
$BBOLD Part (c) $EBOLD
The two-step ahead predictor for this model is
\[
\hat{x}_{60}(2)=$alpha\hat{x}_{60}(1)   = $data[2].
\]
$BR
$BBOLD Part (d) $EBOLD
From above, the approximate 95% prediction interval for the value above is
\[
\hat{x}_{60}(2) \pm 1.96\times $sigma\sqrt{1+\left( $alpha+$beta\right) ^{2}}.
\]
The upper bound is therefore \(\hat{x}_{60}(2) +1.96\times  $sigma\sqrt{1+\left( $alpha+$beta\right) ^{2}}=\) $data[3]. 
$BR
$BR
$BBOLD Part (e) $EBOLD
The three-step ahead predictor for this model is
\[
\hat{x}_{60}(3) = $alpha\hat{x}_{60}(2).
\]
The approximate 95% prediction interval for the value above is
\[
\hat{x}_{60}(3) \pm 1.96\times $sigma\sqrt{1+\left(  $alpha+$beta\right) ^{2}+\left( $alpha^{2}+$alpha\times $beta\right)^{2}}.
\] 
The lower bound is \(\hat{x}_{60}(3) -1.96\times  $sigma\sqrt{1+\left( $alpha+$beta\right) ^{2}+\left(  $alpha^{2}+$alpha\times $beta\right) ^{2}}=\) $data[4]. 


END_SOLUTION

